comments.text:
Felix Baumgartner's supersonic freefall from 128k' - Mission Highlights 
------------

After flying to an altitude of 39,045 meters (128,100 feet) in a 
helium-filled balloon, Felix Baumgartner completed a record breaking jump 
for the ages from the edge of space, exactly 65 years after Chuck Yeager 
first broke the sound barrier flying in an experimental rocket-powered 
airplane. Felix reached a maximum of speed of 1,357.6 km/h or 843.6 
mph(Mach 1.25) through the near vacuum of the stratosphere before being 
slowed by the atmosphere later during his 4:20 minute long freefall. The 
43-year-old Austrian skydiving expert also broke two other world records 
(highest freefall, highest manned balloon flight), leaving the one for the 
longest freefall to project mentor Col. Joe Kittinger.﻿

slight curve relative to the horizon. It is not an aircraft and there is no 
other explanation for it, other than being the space station.

I've read a few books on NASA. (authors include Gene Kranz, Chris Hadfield, 
Buzz Aldrin etc. I also have many more to read from Deke Slayon, Michael 
Collins, Chris Kraft, Niel Armstrong, Gene Cernan, John Glenn etc. From 
what I've read so far, everything links up and nothing has two sides to it.

I've also researched from several of thousands of sources - and once again, 
everything I've read seems to say similar things to everything else.

From the TV documentaries I've seen, the same facts and figures appear, 
opinions are similar, and footage and photos so no signs of being edited.

My research is minimal, although I wouldn't say I 'blindly' believe in
